WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.329 --> 00:00:04.996
(mid-tempo reserved music)

00:00:30.120 --> 00:00:31.770
- Welcome to a Conversation with History.

00:00:31.770 --> 00:00:33.280
I'm Harry Kreisler

00:00:33.280 --> 00:00:35.300
of the Institute of International Studies.

00:00:35.300 --> 00:00:37.770
Our guest today is Christof Koch,

00:00:37.770 --> 00:00:40.480
who is the Lois and Victor Troendle

00:00:40.480 --> 00:00:44.505
Professor of Cognitive and
Behavioral Biology at Caltech,

00:00:44.505 --> 00:00:48.580
and the author most recently
of The Quest for Consciousness.

00:00:48.580 --> 00:00:50.240
He is on the Berkeley campus

00:00:50.240 --> 00:00:54.730
to give the Foerster lecture
on the Immortality of the Soul.

00:00:54.730 --> 00:00:56.260
Christof, welcome to Berkeley.

00:00:56.260 --> 00:00:57.160
- Good morning, Harry.

00:00:57.160 --> 00:00:58.680
- Where were you born and raised?

00:00:58.680 --> 00:01:01.120
- In the Midwest, in Kansas
City, believe it or not.

00:01:01.120 --> 00:01:02.810
- Surprising, surprising.

00:01:02.810 --> 00:01:05.740
How did you happen to be
in America for your birth?

00:01:05.740 --> 00:01:07.894
- I talk like our governor does.

00:01:07.894 --> 00:01:09.373
- (laughs) That's right!

00:01:10.410 --> 00:01:12.700
- My parents were diplomats

00:01:12.700 --> 00:01:13.900
with the German state department,

00:01:13.900 --> 00:01:15.840
so they happened to be in Kansas City

00:01:15.840 --> 00:01:17.710
because there turned out
to be lots of Germans there

00:01:17.710 --> 00:01:19.620
who emigrated there after the war.

00:01:19.620 --> 00:01:20.453
So, I moved around.

00:01:20.453 --> 00:01:22.040
I have a French Baccalaureate,

00:01:22.040 --> 00:01:22.987
and then I lived in Morocco,

00:01:22.987 --> 00:01:25.000
and in Holland, and in Canada.

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:26.900
- Mm hmm, so, a citizen of the world.

00:01:26.900 --> 00:01:28.640
Looking back, how do
you think your parents

00:01:28.640 --> 00:01:30.490
shaped your thinking about the world?

00:01:31.860 --> 00:01:33.580
- Well, since I moved every three years,

00:01:33.580 --> 00:01:34.880
I didn't have so many, you know,

00:01:34.880 --> 00:01:36.500
it's difficult to acquire
long-term friends,

00:01:36.500 --> 00:01:40.990
so I mean everything was,
we are a very tight family.

00:01:40.990 --> 00:01:43.150
So, all my intellectual upbringing,

00:01:43.150 --> 00:01:45.793
and my desires, my passions,
I have from my parents.

00:01:47.200 --> 00:01:51.543
- And when did you get the
science bug, so to speak?

00:01:52.670 --> 00:01:54.940
What led you into science?

00:01:54.940 --> 00:01:57.050
- Well, I mean, from eight, nine,

00:01:57.050 --> 00:01:59.100
or 10 I wanted to be a zoologist.

00:01:59.100 --> 00:02:01.580
I wanted to be a zoo
director and a zoologist.

00:02:01.580 --> 00:02:03.710
And then somewhere at age 13 or 14,

00:02:03.710 --> 00:02:04.920
I wanted to be a physicist,

00:02:04.920 --> 00:02:06.848
and then I studied physics.

00:02:06.848 --> 00:02:09.770
I guess it shows you the
importance of role models.

00:02:09.770 --> 00:02:11.830
I grew up reading books
about you know Einstein,

00:02:11.830 --> 00:02:15.993
and Heisenberg, and Planck,
and all these physicists,

00:02:17.200 --> 00:02:19.400
and that was terribly influential for me.

00:02:19.400 --> 00:02:21.260
And then when I decided upon a university,

00:02:21.260 --> 00:02:22.940
well, I never really made
a conscious decision,

00:02:22.940 --> 00:02:24.150
it was always clear I was gonna go

00:02:24.150 --> 00:02:26.190
to a university and study physics.

00:02:26.190 --> 00:02:27.230
That's what I did.

00:02:27.230 --> 00:02:31.100
- And when one looks at your
degrees and the subject matter,

00:02:31.100 --> 00:02:36.100
you really have covered
the gambit of the sciences.

00:02:36.400 --> 00:02:38.940
You have a French baccalaureate,

00:02:38.940 --> 00:02:43.940
you studied physics and
philosophy at Tubingen in Germany,

00:02:44.020 --> 00:02:45.930
and master in physics

00:02:45.930 --> 00:02:49.727
and a Ph.D. in nonlinear
information processing

00:02:49.727 --> 00:02:53.950
in the dendritic trees
of arbitrary geometry.

00:02:53.950 --> 00:02:54.899
- That's correct.

00:02:54.899 --> 00:02:59.899
- (laughs) So, science
has come to you easily?

00:03:00.820 --> 00:03:03.900
I mean there was a kind of
a natural coming together

00:03:03.900 --> 00:03:04.970
with these different subjects,

00:03:04.970 --> 00:03:06.840
or did one set of problems lead you

00:03:06.840 --> 00:03:08.716
to another set of problems?

00:03:08.716 --> 00:03:10.747
- Well, both, I mean I
always wanted to be a,

00:03:10.747 --> 00:03:13.110
I mean at least from a very early age on.

00:03:13.110 --> 00:03:15.350
I love science, I love the
process of doing science.

00:03:15.350 --> 00:03:17.290
If I could, I'd like to know everything

00:03:17.290 --> 00:03:18.240
there is about the world.

00:03:18.240 --> 00:03:19.073
But of course, you have to realize

00:03:19.073 --> 00:03:20.880
as you get older you have to concentrate

00:03:20.880 --> 00:03:23.660
on one particular aspect of it.

00:03:23.660 --> 00:03:26.630
And so I chose to
concentrate on the brain,

00:03:26.630 --> 00:03:28.930
how the brain processes information,

00:03:28.930 --> 00:03:30.370
in what way is it like a computer,

00:03:30.370 --> 00:03:32.550
in what way is it
different from a computer.

00:03:32.550 --> 00:03:33.900
And then over the last 20 years,

00:03:33.900 --> 00:03:36.700
on the problem of consciousness,

00:03:36.700 --> 00:03:40.033
possibly influenced because of
the many philosophers I read.

00:03:40.930 --> 00:03:42.340
- Now help us understand,

00:03:42.340 --> 00:03:44.614
is it fair to call you a
neurobiologist, is that?

00:03:44.614 --> 00:03:45.693
- [Christof] Yes.

00:03:45.693 --> 00:03:50.000
- Yes, help us understand
the skills and temperament

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:51.550
required to do that kind of work,

00:03:51.550 --> 00:03:53.113
before we talk about the work.

00:03:54.420 --> 00:03:57.490
- I mean it's different
from being a physicist.

00:03:57.490 --> 00:04:00.280
So in some parts of
science, like in physics,

00:04:00.280 --> 00:04:01.940
there are a few deep principles,

00:04:01.940 --> 00:04:04.750
like general relativity,
or like electrodynamics,

00:04:04.750 --> 00:04:06.865
and then you can use a few principles

00:04:06.865 --> 00:04:09.980
to explain a large number
of facts in the universe,

00:04:09.980 --> 00:04:11.973
like the cosmos and its evolution,

00:04:11.973 --> 00:04:14.480
and how particles move inside the cosmos,

00:04:14.480 --> 00:04:16.410
and how planets act, and
things like, and you know,

00:04:16.410 --> 00:04:17.720
why if I drop my keys,

00:04:17.720 --> 00:04:19.780
why do they fall to the floor, et cetera.

00:04:19.780 --> 00:04:21.270
Biology's a very different character.

00:04:21.270 --> 00:04:23.330
Biology, there are very
few common principles,

00:04:23.330 --> 00:04:24.813
except maybe the theory of evolution.

00:04:24.813 --> 00:04:26.310
There's a gigantic,

00:04:26.310 --> 00:04:27.920
a gargantuan number of facts

00:04:27.920 --> 00:04:29.850
that you have to know
and have to assemble,

00:04:29.850 --> 00:04:34.730
so you really have to be
in the field a long time.

00:04:34.730 --> 00:04:39.730
So, children prodigies exist
in maybe in mathematics

00:04:39.780 --> 00:04:42.070
or in music, or maybe in some
areas of theoretical physics,

00:04:42.070 --> 00:04:43.130
but don't exist in biology

00:04:43.130 --> 00:04:44.590
because in biology you just have to know

00:04:44.590 --> 00:04:45.530
a huge number of facts,

00:04:45.530 --> 00:04:47.650
which of course takes time to acquire,

00:04:47.650 --> 00:04:49.530
because you know each biological system is

00:04:49.530 --> 00:04:51.280
sort of an accident of evolution,

00:04:51.280 --> 00:04:52.140
and to understand it,

00:04:52.140 --> 00:04:54.200
you have to understand
its unique circumstances,

00:04:54.200 --> 00:04:57.470
and how this animal's
different from this animal.

00:04:57.470 --> 00:05:00.090
And you have to just
know molecular biology,

00:05:00.090 --> 00:05:02.940
and biochemistry, and
neuroscience, and psychology,

00:05:02.940 --> 00:05:04.970
and the theory of evolution.

00:05:04.970 --> 00:05:08.320
So, it requires a much
larger number of facts

00:05:08.320 --> 00:05:10.590
to explain any given observation.

00:05:10.590 --> 00:05:11.920
- What about temperament?

00:05:11.920 --> 00:05:14.130
I know at looking at your website,

00:05:14.130 --> 00:05:15.890
that you are adventuresome,

00:05:15.890 --> 00:05:17.563
you're a mountain climber, and so on.

00:05:17.563 --> 00:05:19.730
Is that just you personally,

00:05:19.730 --> 00:05:24.730
or what about the temperament
of somebody doing this work

00:05:24.730 --> 00:05:27.370
that brings together so many fields?

00:05:27.370 --> 00:05:28.400
- Well, you have to love risk,

00:05:28.400 --> 00:05:30.070
which I guess is what
you have to love doing

00:05:30.070 --> 00:05:32.620
if you like to climb rocks and mountains.

00:05:32.620 --> 00:05:34.300
And you have to be in
it for the long term.

00:05:34.300 --> 00:05:36.490
It takes a long time, you
have to be very patient,

00:05:36.490 --> 00:05:38.340
and you have to love the process.

00:05:38.340 --> 00:05:39.500
You have to love the process,

00:05:39.500 --> 00:05:42.810
because the action itself
takes place over many years.

00:05:42.810 --> 00:05:45.330
You have to fight to get
money to do the research,

00:05:45.330 --> 00:05:46.880
the research itself is very difficult,

00:05:46.880 --> 00:05:48.560
it's technically very demanding,

00:05:48.560 --> 00:05:50.280
it takes long, long hours,

00:05:50.280 --> 00:05:51.890
and then you have to
fight to get it published

00:05:51.890 --> 00:05:53.600
and get it accepted by your peers.

00:05:53.600 --> 00:05:56.380
And so you know, this can
take five, six, seven years

00:05:56.380 --> 00:05:57.300
for a single experiment,

00:05:57.300 --> 00:06:00.870
to run through this entire
life-cycle of one experiment.

00:06:00.870 --> 00:06:02.623
And so, you really have
to be passionate about it,

00:06:02.623 --> 00:06:05.130
and you have to be
passionate about the process,

00:06:05.130 --> 00:06:07.620
and the rewards that are
sort of very long-term,

00:06:07.620 --> 00:06:08.720
distant in the future.

00:06:09.680 --> 00:06:12.080
I mean the objective of what
it's like to get tenure,

00:06:12.080 --> 00:06:13.010
you get a good salary,

00:06:13.010 --> 00:06:14.080
something like that.

00:06:14.080 --> 00:06:15.110
So you have to do it

00:06:15.110 --> 00:06:17.310
because you love the act of thinking about

00:06:17.310 --> 00:06:18.777
and trying to understand a phenomenon,

00:06:18.777 --> 00:06:21.090
trying to collect data,
and sift through the data,

00:06:21.090 --> 00:06:23.950
and try to find, you know
sort the chaff from the wheat,

00:06:23.950 --> 00:06:25.010
and do things like that.

00:06:25.010 --> 00:06:28.430
- Mm hmm, now I know that
one of your main projects

00:06:28.430 --> 00:06:32.220
in the last few years
is covered in this book,

00:06:32.220 --> 00:06:37.220
The Quest for Consciousness:
A Neurobiological Approach.

00:06:37.250 --> 00:06:40.550
And what I first wanna ask you is to talk

00:06:40.550 --> 00:06:43.780
about your collaboration
with Francis Crick,

00:06:43.780 --> 00:06:47.040
because I know that the two of you working

00:06:47.040 --> 00:06:51.460
over a number of years came to define

00:06:51.460 --> 00:06:53.380
a kind of intellectual frame.

00:06:53.380 --> 00:06:56.790
But talk a little about
that intellectual process

00:06:56.790 --> 00:06:58.023
between the two of you.

00:07:01.496 --> 00:07:05.220
- And so Francis, has I
guess, the way he works,

00:07:05.220 --> 00:07:06.540
he never had a lab,

00:07:06.540 --> 00:07:08.160
he never worked with a
large number of people

00:07:08.160 --> 00:07:09.360
at any given point in time.

00:07:09.360 --> 00:07:10.800
He worked with one or two people,

00:07:10.800 --> 00:07:13.260
most famously, of course, was Jim Watson,

00:07:13.260 --> 00:07:16.610
and then also with Sydney
Brenner, with Graeme Mitchison.

00:07:16.610 --> 00:07:19.850
And so we worked for
close to almost 20 years.

00:07:19.850 --> 00:07:23.710
When I moved from MIT to Caltech in '86

00:07:23.710 --> 00:07:27.210
we started to interact and
we met on a monthly basis

00:07:27.210 --> 00:07:28.390
to talk about the brain.

00:07:28.390 --> 00:07:30.920
And then in 1989,

00:07:30.920 --> 00:07:33.900
we started becoming very
intensely interested

00:07:33.900 --> 00:07:36.850
because there was a certain
neurobiological discovery,

00:07:36.850 --> 00:07:37.737
we became very interested in that

00:07:37.737 --> 00:07:40.230
and we thought maybe this would be

00:07:40.230 --> 00:07:43.240
one of the critical features,

00:07:43.240 --> 00:07:46.090
a signature of consciousness in the brain.

00:07:46.090 --> 00:07:49.363
And I think what Francis
appreciated about our interaction,

00:07:50.597 --> 00:07:51.850
well, the energy level,

00:07:51.850 --> 00:07:54.060
but also that you know

00:07:54.060 --> 00:07:55.960
because he's such a well-known person,

00:07:57.060 --> 00:08:00.730
many people didn't really
criticize any of his idea,

00:08:00.730 --> 00:08:01.563
and he didn't like that.

00:08:01.563 --> 00:08:02.560
He wanted to be criticized.

00:08:02.560 --> 00:08:04.863
He was prodigious at throwing out ideas.

00:08:05.738 --> 00:08:08.710
Some were very smart,
some were very perceptive,

00:08:08.710 --> 00:08:11.570
some were not so, some were just crazy,

00:08:11.570 --> 00:08:14.100
but you know, you have
this fantastic person,

00:08:14.100 --> 00:08:16.010
this creative genius, who can
just throw out these ideas,

00:08:16.010 --> 00:08:18.210
and he wants a sounding board to tell you,

00:08:18.210 --> 00:08:19.070
well, this isn't gonna work,

00:08:19.070 --> 00:08:22.360
this is really great but
this is totally silly,

00:08:22.360 --> 00:08:26.590
and really have a give or
take over many, many hours.

00:08:26.590 --> 00:08:27.900
I mean that was his style of working,

00:08:27.900 --> 00:08:28.739
that you came in the morning

00:08:28.739 --> 00:08:32.140
and from 10 o'clock till six o'clock

00:08:32.140 --> 00:08:33.620
you would just discuss paper.

00:08:33.620 --> 00:08:34.830
He would go through the evidence,

00:08:34.830 --> 00:08:36.920
he would sift the data, discuss it,

00:08:36.920 --> 00:08:38.150
look at it from different light,

00:08:38.150 --> 00:08:39.610
reject it, have a hypothesis,

00:08:39.610 --> 00:08:41.350
reject it again, then dinner,

00:08:41.350 --> 00:08:45.230
and then usually after dinner
that process would continue.

00:08:45.230 --> 00:08:47.830
He kept this up till
essentially the day he died.

00:08:47.830 --> 00:08:51.460
- Mm hmm, and what we have here is

00:08:51.460 --> 00:08:54.800
we're on the threshold of a revolution

00:08:54.800 --> 00:08:57.580
in the biological sciences on the question

00:08:57.580 --> 00:08:59.340
of how the brain works

00:08:59.340 --> 00:09:02.050
and the biological basis of consciousness.

00:09:02.050 --> 00:09:05.700
So what in a way this collaboration was

00:09:05.700 --> 00:09:10.040
was the formation of a kind of theory

00:09:10.040 --> 00:09:12.820
which could then be tested
by empirical research.

00:09:12.820 --> 00:09:14.020
Is that fair?

00:09:14.020 --> 00:09:19.000
Is that a fair way to look
at the article that resulted

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:21.690
which I guess you published
in Science and Nature,

00:09:21.690 --> 00:09:23.790
laying out an intellectual framework?

00:09:23.790 --> 00:09:26.570
- Yes, it's unfortunately,
it's too ambitious

00:09:26.570 --> 00:09:27.700
to call it a theory.

00:09:27.700 --> 00:09:29.200
It's a framework.

00:09:29.200 --> 00:09:30.033
And there's a difference.

00:09:30.033 --> 00:09:32.150
A theory is something much more solid

00:09:32.150 --> 00:09:34.740
where you can make very
specific predictions,

00:09:34.740 --> 00:09:36.693
like the theory of relativity.

00:09:38.200 --> 00:09:41.540
This is more a framework
for approaching the problem

00:09:41.540 --> 00:09:46.080
in a way that allows you for
a sustained research program

00:09:46.080 --> 00:09:49.390
at the end of which you
will understand much more

00:09:49.390 --> 00:09:51.550
about consciousness, and hopefully,

00:09:51.550 --> 00:09:54.020
that's a hope right now, a fond hope,

00:09:54.020 --> 00:09:55.870
that ultimately you will solve the problem

00:09:55.870 --> 00:09:58.767
at the heart of the classical
conceived mind/body problem.

00:09:58.767 --> 00:10:01.110
Namely, how do feelings
get into the world?

00:10:01.110 --> 00:10:02.470
How is it that the physical system,

00:10:02.470 --> 00:10:03.439
like your brain or my brain,

00:10:03.439 --> 00:10:05.630
can have feelings of pain or pleasure?

00:10:05.630 --> 00:10:06.463
Of being me?

00:10:06.463 --> 00:10:07.296
Of being angry?

00:10:07.296 --> 00:10:10.473
- Mm hmm, now help us understand,

00:10:10.473 --> 00:10:12.670
I think we know what consciousness is,

00:10:12.670 --> 00:10:14.760
or people think they do, but explain that.

00:10:14.760 --> 00:10:17.470
Now I think you refer
to Searle's definition,

00:10:17.470 --> 00:10:22.470
but help us kind of
understand what the it is

00:10:23.470 --> 00:10:27.610
that you're trying to
characterize, and then find

00:10:27.610 --> 00:10:30.590
the sources of that in
the biology of the brain.

00:10:30.590 --> 00:10:33.230
- Yeah, John Searle you know
says that consciousness,

00:10:33.230 --> 00:10:35.740
what you have when you wake
up in the morning you have it,

00:10:35.740 --> 00:10:36.580
you have it all day,

00:10:36.580 --> 00:10:38.960
and then it goes away when
you go into deep sleep,

00:10:38.960 --> 00:10:41.020
and then in dreams, of
course, you also have it.

00:10:41.020 --> 00:10:44.190
So, it's the most fundamental
feature of the world.

00:10:44.190 --> 00:10:46.240
It's the way how we experience the world.

00:10:48.660 --> 00:10:50.380
When I feel pain or feel pleasure,

00:10:50.380 --> 00:10:54.790
I see you, or I'm angry,
or I know I'm Christof,

00:10:54.790 --> 00:10:56.170
I know I'm gonna die,

00:10:56.170 --> 00:10:58.150
those are all conscious sensations.

00:10:58.150 --> 00:10:59.550
Philosophers have the term qualia,

00:10:59.550 --> 00:11:01.780
so consciousness is made
up these different qualia.

00:11:01.780 --> 00:11:03.490
Qualia for being angry, for seeing red,

00:11:03.490 --> 00:11:04.860
and that is fundamentally the way,

00:11:04.860 --> 00:11:05.850
how we experience the world.

00:11:05.850 --> 00:11:08.320
To experience the world
means to be conscious of it.

00:11:08.320 --> 00:11:10.770
It turns out there are many
things that I can do in my body.

00:11:10.770 --> 00:11:12.460
In fact, most of the things I do

00:11:12.460 --> 00:11:15.240
without having any
conscious access to them.

00:11:15.240 --> 00:11:17.210
My digestive system works wonderful

00:11:17.210 --> 00:11:18.300
without me knowing about it.

00:11:18.300 --> 00:11:19.393
There're a hundred million neurons

00:11:19.393 --> 00:11:21.940
roughly down here in your
gut, a hundred million.

00:11:21.940 --> 00:11:23.160
We're not conscious of them.

00:11:23.160 --> 00:11:24.289
When you run, when you climb,

00:11:24.289 --> 00:11:26.700
when you dance, when you drive a car,

00:11:26.700 --> 00:11:28.310
when you bike, you're
doing things effortlessly.

00:11:28.310 --> 00:11:29.330
When you run down a mountain,

00:11:29.330 --> 00:11:31.120
you run very quickly and you have no idea

00:11:31.120 --> 00:11:32.950
how you're doing it, you're
doing it unconsciously.

00:11:32.950 --> 00:11:35.560
When I talk, it's not
that there's a person,

00:11:35.560 --> 00:11:36.470
a Christof, in my head

00:11:36.470 --> 00:11:39.140
who sort of puts these words together,

00:11:39.140 --> 00:11:40.420
and then in German or English,

00:11:40.420 --> 00:11:42.770
in the verb and the
adjective and sends it out.

00:11:42.770 --> 00:11:44.610
No, I have a vague idea
and the next thing,

00:11:44.610 --> 00:11:46.380
I hear these words coming out of my mouth.

00:11:46.380 --> 00:11:47.870
So, we know there are many things,

00:11:47.870 --> 00:11:49.540
in fact, the majority
of things in my brain,

00:11:49.540 --> 00:11:50.998
I don't have conscious access to.

00:11:50.998 --> 00:11:52.660
Certain things I do have
conscious access to.

00:11:52.660 --> 00:11:54.120
Where's the difference?

00:11:54.120 --> 00:11:55.482
How is this possible?

00:11:55.482 --> 00:11:58.930
- And you actually refer to
this as kind of a zombie effect,

00:11:58.930 --> 00:12:00.110
namely, not the consciousness,

00:12:00.110 --> 00:12:02.620
but these things that we do automatically.

00:12:02.620 --> 00:12:03.960
- Yeah, so we have all these zombies

00:12:03.960 --> 00:12:05.330
that we use all the time.

00:12:05.330 --> 00:12:06.600
In fact, life wouldn't be possible

00:12:06.600 --> 00:12:08.770
without these zombie agents in our head.

00:12:08.770 --> 00:12:12.300
And so this makes you know,

00:12:12.300 --> 00:12:13.970
makes for an interesting research strategy

00:12:13.970 --> 00:12:15.980
because I can now ask at
the neurological level,

00:12:15.980 --> 00:12:16.813
at the brain level,

00:12:16.813 --> 00:12:18.100
where's the difference
between those systems

00:12:18.100 --> 00:12:19.610
that mediate my zombie behaviors

00:12:19.610 --> 00:12:23.250
and those systems that
actually require consciousness?

00:12:23.250 --> 00:12:25.210
And it's a scandal, and
Francis always felt this,

00:12:25.210 --> 00:12:27.800
it's a scandal if science
leaves out consciousness.

00:12:27.800 --> 00:12:29.090
You know it's less today,

00:12:29.090 --> 00:12:31.170
but certainly 10 or 20
years ago when we started,

00:12:31.170 --> 00:12:33.120
many scientists, probably the majority,

00:12:33.120 --> 00:12:34.480
said, well, you know consciousness,

00:12:34.480 --> 00:12:35.980
you've got to leave that
to the religious people,

00:12:35.980 --> 00:12:37.420
you've got to leave that
to the philosophers,

00:12:37.420 --> 00:12:39.550
you've got to leave that to
the you know New Age cult.

00:12:39.550 --> 00:12:41.360
That's not something scientists can study.

00:12:41.360 --> 00:12:42.193
But that's silly.

00:12:42.193 --> 00:12:43.680
I mean we are conscious

00:12:43.680 --> 00:12:47.920
and I believe it's the most
essential aspect of my life,

00:12:47.920 --> 00:12:49.137
it's the fact that I'm a conscious being,

00:12:49.137 --> 00:12:50.053
and if I leave that out,

00:12:50.053 --> 00:12:52.320
then I will forever deprive science

00:12:52.320 --> 00:12:54.450
of one of the key aspects
of the natural world.

00:12:54.450 --> 00:12:56.730
We claim it's a natural phenomenon,

00:12:56.730 --> 00:12:58.310
it exists not here,

00:12:58.310 --> 00:12:59.270
but it seems to exist here,

00:12:59.270 --> 00:13:01.250
so if science has ambition

00:13:01.250 --> 00:13:03.483
that it wants to describe
everything in this universe,

00:13:03.483 --> 00:13:05.740
then it has to describe consciousness.

00:13:05.740 --> 00:13:07.200
In other words, it's just a cop-out.

00:13:07.200 --> 00:13:08.300
Yes, it's difficult,

00:13:08.300 --> 00:13:10.850
it's different than
trying to have a theory

00:13:10.850 --> 00:13:12.160
for how mass is derived,

00:13:12.160 --> 00:13:13.680
but it's nonetheless a natural phenomenon

00:13:13.680 --> 00:13:16.023
and we should study it as scientists.

00:13:16.023 --> 00:13:21.023
- Now, one is able to do the
experimentation now, why?

00:13:22.970 --> 00:13:24.761
Because of all of the new technologies

00:13:24.761 --> 00:13:28.390
that are coming on board
that are allowing us

00:13:28.390 --> 00:13:29.970
to look at the brain?

00:13:29.970 --> 00:13:32.330
- Yeah, I mean, we can now
do routinely in animals,

00:13:32.330 --> 00:13:34.770
we can monitor individual nerve cells.

00:13:34.770 --> 00:13:35.603
So you have to understand

00:13:35.603 --> 00:13:37.030
if you wanna understand chemistry,

00:13:37.030 --> 00:13:38.850
or if you want to understand physics,

00:13:38.850 --> 00:13:40.060
you need to know about atoms,

00:13:40.060 --> 00:13:41.640
and you need to know about molecules,

00:13:41.640 --> 00:13:43.330
and you need to know how they interact.

00:13:43.330 --> 00:13:46.180
You can't do chemistry without
knowing about molecules.

00:13:46.180 --> 00:13:48.110
Likewise, if you wanna
understand consciousness

00:13:48.110 --> 00:13:50.840
or perception or memory or thought,

00:13:50.840 --> 00:13:53.440
and what happens if these
goes wrong in mental diseases,

00:13:53.440 --> 00:13:54.910
you need to know about nerve cells,

00:13:54.910 --> 00:13:56.550
and you need to know how they interact.

00:13:56.550 --> 00:13:58.810
And we today, in 2006,

00:13:58.810 --> 00:14:00.620
better than before in
any point in history,

00:14:00.620 --> 00:14:02.230
we can monitor nerve cells,

00:14:02.230 --> 00:14:03.370
we can listen to them,

00:14:03.370 --> 00:14:04.370
we can record them,

00:14:04.370 --> 00:14:06.550
we can stimulate them, we
can do all sorts of things,

00:14:06.550 --> 00:14:09.550
both in animals as well as in humans.

00:14:09.550 --> 00:14:11.570
In humans it's much more
difficult, of course.

00:14:11.570 --> 00:14:13.150
We have brain imaging, which is cool,

00:14:13.150 --> 00:14:15.740
but it's a very low spatial resolution.

00:14:15.740 --> 00:14:17.680
But we have all these
tools that enable us now

00:14:17.680 --> 00:14:19.510
to begin to monitor the brain

00:14:19.510 --> 00:14:21.720
at the appropriate level of resolution.

00:14:21.720 --> 00:14:24.800
And so now we think it's the time

00:14:24.800 --> 00:14:28.010
to start having experiments,
and people are doing it,

00:14:28.010 --> 00:14:30.233
to study the neural
basis of consciousness.

00:14:31.113 --> 00:14:33.830
- And so the, another challenge, I guess,

00:14:33.830 --> 00:14:37.294
is to devise the experiments,

00:14:37.294 --> 00:14:40.740
to create reactions and
then put this together,

00:14:40.740 --> 00:14:42.230
what we're now able to see.

00:14:42.230 --> 00:14:44.690
Is that the name of the game here?

00:14:44.690 --> 00:14:46.020
- Yeah, I mean this is what scientists do.

00:14:46.020 --> 00:14:49.353
I try to do the right control,
do the correct experiment.

00:14:50.430 --> 00:14:51.540
Which, as I mentioned before,

00:14:51.540 --> 00:14:55.560
may take you many years
to figure out some fact

00:14:55.560 --> 00:14:58.263
about the brain basis of consciousness.

00:14:59.130 --> 00:15:03.810
- Is there a thumbnail sketch of the brain

00:15:03.810 --> 00:15:06.393
that you could give a general audience,

00:15:07.815 --> 00:15:12.350
where the most exciting points

00:15:12.350 --> 00:15:15.123
of direction seem to be in your research?

00:15:17.770 --> 00:15:20.400
- Wait, you want a summary, an
explanation of the brain or?

00:15:20.400 --> 00:15:21.233
- Let me rephrase it.

00:15:21.233 --> 00:15:22.066
It's a bad question.

00:15:22.066 --> 00:15:24.730
In other words, basically,
so let's begin talking

00:15:24.730 --> 00:15:28.340
about what your hypothesis is

00:15:28.340 --> 00:15:33.340
about how the brain works at
this point of consciousness.

00:15:33.420 --> 00:15:37.400
What are the hypotheses that help give you

00:15:37.400 --> 00:15:40.300
an organizing sense of
how to look for things?

00:15:40.300 --> 00:15:41.133
- Okay, so first of all,

00:15:41.133 --> 00:15:42.530
the overall approach that we advocate

00:15:42.530 --> 00:15:44.562
that's now, most people do this,

00:15:44.562 --> 00:15:47.520
is to study what people abbreviate as NCC,

00:15:47.520 --> 00:15:49.250
the neuronal correlate of consciousness.

00:15:49.250 --> 00:15:52.420
Those are the minimal brain, the minimal

00:15:52.420 --> 00:15:54.140
because we know your
entire brain is sufficient

00:15:54.140 --> 00:15:55.210
to give rise to consciousness,

00:15:55.210 --> 00:15:56.670
it does it each and every day.

00:15:56.670 --> 00:15:59.050
But do you really need your eyes to see?

00:15:59.050 --> 00:15:59.900
Well, I can dream.

00:15:59.900 --> 00:16:01.680
My eyes are closed and
I perfectly well dream,

00:16:01.680 --> 00:16:04.170
perfectly formed visual images.

00:16:04.170 --> 00:16:06.170
I can close my eyes and I can visualize,

00:16:06.170 --> 00:16:07.670
so I don't need my eyes.

00:16:07.670 --> 00:16:09.240
Do I need my cerebellum?

00:16:09.240 --> 00:16:11.690
Probably not for visual consciousness

00:16:11.690 --> 00:16:13.250
or probably not for any consciousness.

00:16:13.250 --> 00:16:14.570
So you can ask these question,

00:16:14.570 --> 00:16:16.390
what are the minimal set of mechanisms

00:16:16.390 --> 00:16:19.010
in your head that you need
in order to be conscious?

00:16:19.010 --> 00:16:20.270
Is there a specific neurosignature,

00:16:20.270 --> 00:16:22.314
are there specific types of neurons,

00:16:22.314 --> 00:16:24.870
is there a particular
type of neural activity,

00:16:24.870 --> 00:16:26.420
are there particular types of molecules,

00:16:26.420 --> 00:16:27.800
particular types of synapses,

00:16:27.800 --> 00:16:29.780
do they sit in a particular
part of the brain?

00:16:29.780 --> 00:16:31.820
So you can ask this
whole set of questions,

00:16:31.820 --> 00:16:33.080
and the name of the game is

00:16:33.080 --> 00:16:35.680
to try to isolate those mechanisms

00:16:35.680 --> 00:16:36.890
to really hone in, saying, okay,

00:16:36.890 --> 00:16:40.830
these neurons in this
particular configuration.

00:16:40.830 --> 00:16:42.740
We talk about coalition of
neurons, you have to imagine

00:16:42.740 --> 00:16:44.940
the brain has a very,
very, very large number,

00:16:44.940 --> 00:16:48.530
there are roughly 50 to
100 billion nerve cells,

00:16:48.530 --> 00:16:50.250
and each one is like a little computer.

00:16:50.250 --> 00:16:53.290
Neurons are not sort of
dumb, like a transistor.

00:16:53.290 --> 00:16:55.950
They're very quote, smart,
they're very sophisticated,

00:16:55.950 --> 00:16:58.350
each nerve cell, each neuron,

00:16:58.350 --> 00:16:59.680
and you have 100 billion of them.

00:16:59.680 --> 00:17:02.127
And consciousness may be
a coalition of neurons

00:17:02.127 --> 00:17:04.290
You know, it's little
bit like in a democracy

00:17:04.290 --> 00:17:05.730
when you have coalition that form,

00:17:05.730 --> 00:17:07.570
and that assemble and then disassemble,

00:17:07.570 --> 00:17:10.010
except the time scale is not years like

00:17:10.010 --> 00:17:11.870
in the American electoral system,

00:17:11.870 --> 00:17:13.510
but it's sort of fraction of a second.

00:17:13.510 --> 00:17:14.560
And so, for a hundredth of a millisecond

00:17:14.560 --> 00:17:17.440
you may have this coalition
of five million neurons,

00:17:17.440 --> 00:17:18.760
and they make in code,

00:17:18.760 --> 00:17:19.610
they may give rise to,

00:17:19.610 --> 00:17:23.680
they may be the feeling of
darn it, I'm late today,

00:17:23.680 --> 00:17:25.020
and then this is suppressed

00:17:25.020 --> 00:17:26.870
because then there's this
other five million neurons,

00:17:26.870 --> 00:17:27.790
or 10 million neurons,

00:17:27.790 --> 00:17:30.250
who now give rise to the oh,
I see my daughter over there,

00:17:30.250 --> 00:17:32.470
and you know then the fact that I'm late,

00:17:32.470 --> 00:17:33.420
you know I forget that,

00:17:33.420 --> 00:17:36.676
you know and I become
conscious of my daughter,

00:17:36.676 --> 00:17:37.762
and those neurons in the brain

00:17:37.762 --> 00:17:41.170
that represent my daughter
fire and they are,

00:17:41.170 --> 00:17:42.630
well, this now depends exactly

00:17:42.630 --> 00:17:44.510
on your philosophical predisposition.

00:17:44.510 --> 00:17:46.080
Some people say the firing

00:17:46.080 --> 00:17:48.680
of these neurons is
identical to consciousness.

00:17:48.680 --> 00:17:51.300
Some people say, well, it
correlates with consciousness,

00:17:51.300 --> 00:17:52.880
those are the things that we don't know.

00:17:52.880 --> 00:17:55.480
But what we try to do empirically
where are those neurons?

00:17:55.480 --> 00:17:56.313
Can you track them?

00:17:56.313 --> 00:17:58.150
Can you catch a brief picture of them

00:17:58.150 --> 00:18:00.080
using some fancy imaging techniques?

00:18:00.080 --> 00:18:00.913
Can you influence them?

00:18:00.913 --> 00:18:02.587
Can you move from,

00:18:02.587 --> 00:18:06.460
scientists, very often,
we can just observe.

00:18:06.460 --> 00:18:07.860
So, for example, a
function of brain imaging,

00:18:07.860 --> 00:18:08.850
I put you in a magnet,

00:18:08.850 --> 00:18:12.540
I show you faces, and I see
every time you look at a face,

00:18:12.540 --> 00:18:13.780
this part of the brain lights up.

00:18:13.780 --> 00:18:15.574
People do that routinely.

00:18:15.574 --> 00:18:18.090
So that's observation, that's correlation.

00:18:18.090 --> 00:18:18.950
What I would then like to do,

00:18:18.950 --> 00:18:21.230
I would like to move to
causation, where I can influence.

00:18:21.230 --> 00:18:23.350
What happens if I can
put a probe in your brain

00:18:23.350 --> 00:18:25.690
like a neurosurgeon does
during neurosurgery,

00:18:25.690 --> 00:18:27.590
and I can stimulate that
particular part of the brain?

00:18:27.590 --> 00:18:29.140
Will you then see a face?

00:18:29.140 --> 00:18:31.260
And again, we can begin
to do those experiments

00:18:31.260 --> 00:18:32.093
quite well in animals,

00:18:32.093 --> 00:18:34.200
and we can also do them
in certain contexts,

00:18:34.200 --> 00:18:37.420
for example, in a neurosurgical
context with humans,

00:18:37.420 --> 00:18:40.080
where it can actually begin
to intervene with the brain.

00:18:40.080 --> 00:18:43.382
- And you, as a matter of your strategy,

00:18:43.382 --> 00:18:46.460
are focusing not on all
the different senses

00:18:46.460 --> 00:18:47.980
but really perception.

00:18:47.980 --> 00:18:49.800
Tell us about that choice.

00:18:49.800 --> 00:18:52.310
- Yeah, we focus on vision,
visual consciousness.

00:18:52.310 --> 00:18:53.780
So you know,

00:18:53.780 --> 00:18:55.920
it's a little bit like the
drunkard who lost his keys

00:18:55.920 --> 00:18:59.630
and then looks for his
lost key where the lamp is.

00:18:59.630 --> 00:19:01.260
These are all very,
very difficult problems,

00:19:01.260 --> 00:19:03.590
we haven't made that much
progress over the last 2000 years,

00:19:03.590 --> 00:19:06.680
so when you ask people consciousness,

00:19:06.680 --> 00:19:08.690
they say, oh, you mean self-consciousness.

00:19:08.690 --> 00:19:10.780
Yes, self-consciousness,
one aspect of consciousness,

00:19:10.780 --> 00:19:11.990
but it's very difficult to study.

00:19:11.990 --> 00:19:14.930
The fact that I know I'm
Christof, I know I'm a son,

00:19:14.930 --> 00:19:16.370
I know I have children, et cetera.

00:19:16.370 --> 00:19:17.960
That's very difficult to study empirically

00:19:17.960 --> 00:19:19.624
because it's it's unclear

00:19:19.624 --> 00:19:21.840
to what extent animals have consciousness.

00:19:21.840 --> 00:19:22.740
Some probably do, like the great apes,

00:19:22.740 --> 00:19:25.160
but it's very difficult to study that.

00:19:25.160 --> 00:19:27.310
So, let's study a much
simpler aspect of conscience,

00:19:27.310 --> 00:19:31.250
namely red or blue or seeing
motion or seeing a face.

00:19:31.250 --> 00:19:32.940
We can manipulate that very well.

00:19:32.940 --> 00:19:34.940
We can do what magicians
do since hundreds of years.

00:19:34.940 --> 00:19:37.810
So if you go to a magic show,
you look at the magician.

00:19:37.810 --> 00:19:39.290
The magician will make things disappear

00:19:39.290 --> 00:19:40.510
in front of your eyes.

00:19:40.510 --> 00:19:42.840
He does that partly by
using attention distraction.

00:19:42.840 --> 00:19:44.850
Use a beautiful bikini-clad
assistant next to him

00:19:44.850 --> 00:19:45.750
and you'll be distracted.

00:19:45.750 --> 00:19:46.583
Although you're looking at him,

00:19:46.583 --> 00:19:48.370
you're actually paying attention to her.

00:19:48.370 --> 00:19:50.050
We can do something similar, less sexy,

00:19:50.050 --> 00:19:51.880
but we can do something
similar in the lab.

00:19:51.880 --> 00:19:54.280
Where we can show you things
that you routinely don't see.

00:19:54.280 --> 00:19:55.660
They're in front of your eyes,

00:19:55.660 --> 00:19:57.620
sometimes you see them,
sometimes you don't.

00:19:57.620 --> 00:20:00.000
So now we can use this technique to ask,

00:20:00.000 --> 00:20:02.450
well, in both cases there's
an image present on your eyes,

00:20:02.450 --> 00:20:05.320
but one case you were actually
conscious of the image,

00:20:05.320 --> 00:20:07.210
in the other case you were
not conscious of the image.

00:20:07.210 --> 00:20:08.580
Where's the difference in your brain?

00:20:08.580 --> 00:20:11.710
Is the area X, the consciousness
area that lights up,

00:20:11.710 --> 00:20:12.543
that's one hypothesis.

00:20:12.543 --> 00:20:15.120
That whenever this area lights
up, were you conscious of it?

00:20:15.120 --> 00:20:16.030
Where is that area?

00:20:16.030 --> 00:20:17.390
Is it a series of stages?

00:20:17.390 --> 00:20:18.890
It's not gonna be one area, we know that.

00:20:18.890 --> 00:20:21.750
It's gonna be a series of
areas, probably distributed,

00:20:21.750 --> 00:20:23.030
that have different properties.

00:20:23.030 --> 00:20:24.190
So, we can do this in a magnet,

00:20:24.190 --> 00:20:26.720
we can put you in a magnet and
we can show you these images

00:20:26.720 --> 00:20:28.480
that you see sometimes
and sometimes you don't,

00:20:28.480 --> 00:20:29.410
and we can study that.

00:20:29.410 --> 00:20:30.820
And you can also do this in a monkey,

00:20:30.820 --> 00:20:32.100
or you can do it in a mouse.

00:20:32.100 --> 00:20:34.317
So, vision has the
advantage, visual perception,

00:20:34.317 --> 00:20:36.280
and we can manipulate your visual percept

00:20:36.280 --> 00:20:38.420
very precisely in space and time.

00:20:38.420 --> 00:20:40.220
We can't do that as well as for pain,

00:20:40.220 --> 00:20:42.210
well, it's also very
difficult to recruit people

00:20:42.210 --> 00:20:43.043
to do pain experiments.

00:20:43.043 --> 00:20:43.876
- [Harry] (chuckles) Yeah, right.

00:20:43.876 --> 00:20:45.700
- It's very easy to recruit
them to look at a monitor,

00:20:45.700 --> 00:20:48.423
and you know we pay 'em
twenty bucks to do that.

00:20:49.450 --> 00:20:52.150
And so, it's a tactical reason

00:20:52.150 --> 00:20:55.808
why we focus on visual perception.

00:20:55.808 --> 00:21:00.513
- And some of these experiments
play with, for example,

00:21:02.240 --> 00:21:05.940
when you, these coalitions are often

00:21:05.940 --> 00:21:08.260
in competition, basically, is that?

00:21:08.260 --> 00:21:11.100
- Yes, just like, again, that's
where I think the election

00:21:11.100 --> 00:21:14.380
or democratic analogy or
metaphor is very appropriate.

00:21:14.380 --> 00:21:16.427
You have all these neurons in your head

00:21:16.427 --> 00:21:17.620
and they constantly compete.

00:21:17.620 --> 00:21:18.980
They excite and inhibit each other

00:21:18.980 --> 00:21:20.660
and they constantly compete.

00:21:20.660 --> 00:21:21.760
At any given point in time,

